Thirty-seven trillion cells. That is what you are made of right now. Each one reads genetic instructions three billion letters long. Each one copies itself with almost perfect precision. Each one is a molecular machine of staggering complexity — and every single one of them descended from a single cell that assembled itself from nothing but warm water, chemistry, and time, four billion years ago.

But how? How does a molecule become a cell? How does chemistry become biology? How does something with no purpose, no plan, and no designer build the most complex machinery in the known universe — and then pass it on, unbroken, for four billion years?

In this documentary, we follow the science step by step. From the RNA World — the ancient molecular era before DNA existed — to the first self-replicating molecules, to the fatty acid bubbles that became the first membranes, to the protocells of Jack Szostak's Harvard laboratory, to the mystery of why all life is left-handed, to the ribosome — the most ancient machine on Earth — and finally to LUCA, the last common ancestor of every living thing that has ever existed.

This is not a story about miracles. It is a story about chemistry following its own laws, over vast spans of time, building something extraordinary from almost nothing.

If this kind of deep science moves you — subscribe. New episodes every week.


